421
00:21:17,279 --> 00:21:22,382
Having worked both in a writer's room for television and for interactive fiction and

422
00:21:22,402 --> 00:21:26,564
games, what do you find are the similarities and what do you find are the greatest differences?

423
00:21:28,048 --> 00:21:29,649
That's a giant question.

424
00:21:29,949 --> 00:21:32,850
So yeah, looking at TV and games, what are working in a

425
00:21:32,870 --> 00:21:33,570
writer's room for both?

426
00:21:33,610 --> 00:21:34,210
What are similar?

427
00:21:34,270 --> 00:21:34,870
What are different?

428
00:21:38,411 --> 00:21:40,251
Needing to write discursively.

429
00:21:40,691 --> 00:21:42,952
When you're writing in games, you have to write with a mind

430
00:21:43,432 --> 00:21:44,632
toward branching structures.

431
00:21:45,152 --> 00:21:47,453
Depending on the type of game, the rigor of those

432
00:21:47,473 --> 00:21:48,313
structures will vary.

433
00:21:48,853 --> 00:21:50,854
But you have to remember that when you're writing for a

434
00:21:50,914 --> 00:21:52,654
show, you're presenting something

435
00:21:52,674 --> 00:21:53,714
your audience watches.

436
00:21:53,814 --> 00:21:55,635
When you're writing for a game, you're presenting

437
00:21:55,695 --> 00:21:57,475
something your audience determines.

438
00:21:58,495 --> 00:22:01,856
They have agency in and in the way that you're writing it,

439
00:22:02,176 --> 00:22:03,557
you're sculpting that agency.

440
00:22:03,657 --> 00:22:07,198
So it's as if you have the player character in the room with you at all times

441
00:22:07,238 --> 00:22:11,099
and you're imagining how the different elements of the story options

442
00:22:11,119 --> 00:22:14,059
that you're presenting will sort of influence them

443
00:22:14,159 --> 00:22:16,040
and their experience of navigating that.

444
00:22:16,080 --> 00:22:18,440
I honestly think it's the hardest thing about writing games

445
00:22:18,841 --> 00:22:20,101
and it's the thing that's most exciting

446
00:22:20,161 --> 00:22:22,221
because we have no idea what we're doing with this still.

447
00:22:22,782 --> 00:22:25,567
We're still figuring out what it means, honestly, to have

448
00:22:25,588 --> 00:22:28,934
the consumer of a story practice agency in the

449
00:22:28,974 --> 00:22:29,896
development of that story.

450
00:22:31,540 --> 00:22:32,121
Thanks for the question.

451
00:22:34,051 --> 00:22:34,932
Yeah.

452
00:22:34,952 --> 00:22:34,992
Hi.

453
00:22:35,572 --> 00:22:37,534
Um, there we go.

454
00:22:37,554 --> 00:22:44,339
Uh, so I thought your, um, words on critiquing junior writers' like habits was very insightful.

455
00:22:44,380 --> 00:22:57,270
I was wondering, uh, if you had any other observations that you found that, like, a junior writer did something very, like, well, uh, that might be applicable to other junior writers, uh, to learn from and improve.

456
00:22:57,902 --> 00:22:59,263
Yeah, that's an interesting question.

457
00:23:00,604 --> 00:23:02,567
Everyone can hear the questions from the mics, yeah?

458
00:23:03,267 --> 00:23:04,609
Okay, good, I'm going to repeat it.

459
00:23:06,391 --> 00:23:10,335
One thing I love about working with new writers is that they haven't become jaded or cynical

460
00:23:10,355 --> 00:23:11,636
yet.

461
00:23:11,956 --> 00:23:15,580
And that's, it's funny, but it's honestly true.

462
00:23:15,600 --> 00:23:19,724
And I think outside of that.

463
00:23:20,927 --> 00:23:23,107
You get into a writer's room, it's because you're excellent.

464
00:23:23,307 --> 00:23:25,528
You've done something really well to get to that place.

465
00:23:25,728 --> 00:23:29,529
But at the same time, your education is about to begin,

466
00:23:30,029 --> 00:23:30,409
for real.

467
00:23:31,269 --> 00:23:34,290
So I tell my junior writers, I want them to talk as much as

468
00:23:34,350 --> 00:23:34,710
anyone else.

469
00:23:34,730 --> 00:23:35,710
I want them to ask questions.

470
00:23:35,750 --> 00:23:36,690
I want them to get involved.

471
00:23:36,970 --> 00:23:40,071
I want them not to be afraid of failure, or looking stupid,

472
00:23:40,091 --> 00:23:40,691
or any of that.

473
00:23:41,131 --> 00:23:44,232
But it's that enthusiasm that they really have going for

474
00:23:44,252 --> 00:23:46,993
them that I find joyful to work with.

475
00:23:48,053 --> 00:23:49,073
Thank you for that question.

476
00:23:50,160 --> 00:23:50,341
Yeah?

477
00:23:50,982 --> 00:23:51,482
Hi, thanks.

478
00:23:52,704 --> 00:23:58,934
I was wondering if you had any challenges working on the culture of, say, the writer's

479
00:23:58,994 --> 00:24:02,660
room versus the culture of the organization that you work for as a whole?

480
00:24:02,720 --> 00:24:02,960
Is it...

481
00:24:04,035 --> 00:24:07,576
with their discrepancies between how you run a writer's room.

482
00:24:07,596 --> 00:24:10,538
Because I work at a company where we're trying to establish

483
00:24:10,578 --> 00:24:16,380
writers' rooms and just the idea, how do you merge the two

484
00:24:16,980 --> 00:24:18,181
cultures, I guess?

485
00:24:18,281 --> 00:24:19,722
That's a really insightful question.

486
00:24:20,462 --> 00:24:23,403
I mean, it varies, obviously, from what kind of

487
00:24:23,443 --> 00:24:25,264
organization you're in and what kind of room you want to have.

488
00:24:26,480 --> 00:24:30,843
At Deck Nine, the writing group is also the core design group.

489
00:24:31,384 --> 00:24:34,886
We have level designers who are much better at many kinds of design than we are, but we're

490
00:24:34,906 --> 00:24:35,587
narrative designers.

491
00:24:35,607 --> 00:24:38,549
We write code, we iterate on gameplay mechanics and things like that.

492
00:24:38,569 --> 00:24:42,511
And because of that, we are essentially the start of the content pipeline.

493
00:24:43,652 --> 00:24:46,714
So we have a really autonomous culture in that regard.

494
00:24:47,655 --> 00:24:51,377
I think, like many elements of software development, the most important...

495
00:24:52,227 --> 00:24:53,888
Path forward is the one that works.

496
00:24:54,608 --> 00:24:56,729
